    "summary": "Kievan Rus (c. 882–1240 AD) was the first East Slavic state — a loose federation of principalities centered on Kiev (modern Kyiv) that formed the foundation of the later Russian, Ukrainian, and Belarusian nations. Founded according to tradition when the Varangian (Norse) chieftain Rurik established himself at Novgorod (c. 862 AD), and consolidated when Oleg captured Kiev around 882 AD and made it his capital, Kievan Rus was a product of Varangian Norse merchants using the river route from the Baltic to the Black Sea ('the route from the Varangians to the Greeks') to trade with Byzantium.\n\nThe relationship with Byzantium was central to Kievan Rus's development: Norse-Slavic warriors repeatedly attacked Constantinople (860, 907, 941, 968 AD) and negotiated trade agreements; the [[event:2149|Christianization of Rus]] in 988 AD under Prince Vladimir brought Byzantine Orthodox Christianity, writing (Cyrillic script, devised by the Byzantine missionaries Cyril and Methodius), art, and legal traditions to the Slavic world. Kievan Rus at its peak under Yaroslav the Wise (r. 1019–1054) was a major European power, with diplomatic marriages connecting the Rurikid dynasty to the royal families of France, England, Norway, Hungary, and Byzantium. The state fragmented after Yaroslav's death into competing principalities, leaving it vulnerable to the Mongol invasion of 1237–1240 that destroyed Kiev and many other cities.",
